BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Care & Custody: Past Responses to Mental Health
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T050000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T050000Z
UID:7d97e0389519e35b4347be6ff4a317be@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Galter Library is hosting the exhibit\, Care & Custody: Past R
 esponses to Mental Health\, on loan from National Library of Medicine\, Fe
 bruary 9-March 21\, 2026 in the library atrium. It explores the treatment 
 of people with mental health conditions throughout history\, especially in
  the United States\, bringing to light the tension that has existed betwee
 n care and custody. Physicians\, advocates\, families\, and government age
 ncies have all contributed to the shaping of mental health policies. Care 
 and Custody examines this history to understand how the country has moved 
 away from custodial forms of treatment\, toward more inclusive approaches\
 , and worked to protect the rights of people with mental health conditions
 .\nMake sure to see the companion exhibit curated by Galter staff\, Three 
 Steps Forward\, Two Steps Back: The Continued Struggle to Treat Mental Ill
 ness in America\, on display at in the Eckenhoff Reading Room February 9-J
 uly 31\, 2026.\nVisitors not affiliated with Northwestern should email ghs
 l-specialcollections@northwestern.edu to coordinate an appointment to view
  the exhibit.
LOCATION:Ward Building\, 303 E. Chicago Avenue\, Chicago\, IL
URL:https://galter.northwestern.edu/exhibits/24
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Three Steps Forward\, Two Steps Back: The Continued Struggle to Tr
 eat Mental Illness in America
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T050000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T050000Z
UID:9a18fe2f45484a2626dda78899fb5b7c@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:On display in the Eckenhoff Reading Room: Like a path through 
 a maze\, medical and societal responses to mental illness in America have 
 seen shifts and turns of imperfect progress. This exhibit explores both so
 cietal and medical treatments of mental illness in the US from the 18th ce
 ntury to today. It highlights institutional confinement\, medical and phar
 maceutical treatments\, the development of child psychiatry\, and the shif
 t to police as mental illness first responders. Patterns of advancement an
 d retreat carry through each case\, showing the struggle to properly treat
  mental illness continues today. \n\nThis exhibit was created to compleme
 nt the National Library of Medicine’s traveling exhibit\, Care & Custody
 : Past Responses to Mental Health\, on display in the Galter Library atriu
 m February 9-March 21\, 2026. Details about that exhibit are available her
 e.
LOCATION:Ward Building\, 303 E. Chicago Avenue\, Chicago\, IL
URL:https://galter.northwestern.edu/exhibits/28
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Imagine U: Theatre for the Very Young presents Imagine That! & Spl
 ish\, Splash: A Day on the Lake
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T143000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T151500Z
UID:fc25c61bcfb78148d709ca90635ab487@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Director Ellie Levine\nCo-Creator Splish\, Splash: A Day on th
 e Lake Jamal Howard\nArtistic Mentor Lynn Kelso\nCreated in collaboration 
 with Northwestern Undergraduates and 2-5-year-olds at Total Child Preschoo
 l\nJoin us for a vibrant and engaging introduction to the magic of theatre
 \, specially designed for children aged 2-5 and their grown-ups. Two diffe
 rent remounted shows will take place: Imagine That! (3/7 and 3/15) and Spl
 ish\, Splash: A Day on the Lake (3/8 and 3/14).\nOur multi-sensory perform
 ances offer a delightful first taste of live theatre\, crafted by a dedica
 ted team of educational artists who specialize in early childhood developm
 ent alongside undergraduate students focused on theatre for young audience
 s. Come and experience the joy of interactive storytelling and creative ex
 ploration with your little ones!\nImagine That!\nAutumn\, Winter\, and Spr
 ing are on a mission to make a rainbow\, but they need the help of Summer
 —that’s you! In this interactive\, multi-sensory adventure\, preschool
  audiences will use the power of their imagination to bring the colors of 
 the seasons to life.\nApproximate run time: 45 minutes\nSuggested ages: 2-
 5\nSplish\, Splash: A Day on the Lake\nSet sail on a magical journey aroun
 d Lake Michigan! Through music\, puppetry\, and interactive experiences\, 
 our crew of young sailors will explore the wildlife and whimsy of the lake
 .\nApproximate run time: 45 minutes\nSuggested ages: 2-5
LOCATION:Wirtz Center: Hal & Martha Hyer Wallis Theater\, 1949 Campus Driv
 e\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://wirtz.northwestern.edu/imagine-u-theatre-for-the-very-young/
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Norman Fischer Chamber Music Master Class
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T150000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T180000Z
UID:3a7817551ff99da1c60cb1878c436773@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Cellist Norman Fischer\, a lifelong friend of composer George 
 Rochberg\, coaches Bienen student chamber musicians as part of the weeklon
 g colloquium Unearthing Love and Grief in George Rochberg’s Third String
  Quartet.\nFischer was a member of the Concord String Quartet throughout i
 ts 16-year career\, during which the group received two Grammy nominations
  and an Emmy Award. He is currently a member of the Fischer Duo\, together
  with pianist Jeanne Kierman. In addition to specializing in music of Beet
 hoven\, Brahms\, and Schumann\, the Duo has premiered more than 30 new sco
 res by composers including George Rochberg\, Augusta Read Thomas\, Robert 
 Sirota\, Pierre Jalbert\, and Richard Wilson. As a soloist\, Fischer opene
 d the 1995 Tanglewood Music Center season and has given concerto performan
 ces under such conductors as Lukas Foss\, Robert Spano\, Larry Rachleff\, 
 and Efrain Guigui. He is the Herbert S. Autrey Professor of Cello and Dire
 ctor of Chamber Music at Rice University’s Shepherd School of Music.
LOCATION:Patrick G. and Shirley W. Ryan Center for the Musical Arts\, 70 A
 rts Circle\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://www.music.northwestern.edu/events/norman-fischer-chamber-music
 -master-class
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
