BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Raphaella Smits\, guitar
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T003000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T023000Z
UID:6e33e4afa6d02ce73b6ea14de7c77ece@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Part of the Segovia Classical Guitar Series\n"...one of the mo
 st delicate and most cultivated performers of our time."  \n—Diapason 
 \nA renowned guitarist and pedagogue\, Raphaella Smits plays worldwide on 
 eight-string guitars and historical instruments. Alongside her internation
 al touring career\, she has recorded 25 albums to great acclaim. Smits is 
 recognized as a gifted teacher of both guitar and chamber music\, frequent
 ly serving on the juries of prestigious international music competitions. 
 She taught at the Lemmens Institute in Belgium for 36 years and continues 
 to give master classes across Europe\, the Americas\, and Japan. In 1986\,
  Smits was the first woman to win the first prize of the Francisco Tárreg
 a International Guitar Competition in Spain\, earning praise from chairmen
  Andrés Segovia and Narciso Yepes. Smits was recently awarded at the Fest
 ival Guitarras del Mundo in Argentina for her unique contributions to guit
 ar music and culture. \nMauro Giuliani\, Grande ouverture\, Op. 61 \nFer
 nando Sor\, Introduction et variations sur l’air “Malbroug\,” Op. 28
 \nFernando Sor\, Fantaisie pour la guitare dédiée à son ami Ignace Pley
 el\, Op. 7 \nAnton Diabelli\, Sonatina No. 3\, Op. 168 \nFernando Sor\, 
 Etude No. 11\, Op. 6 \nJohann Kaspar Mertz\, Le romantique (Grande fantai
 sie)\nSegovia Classical Guitar Series new subscriptions and single tickets
  are available now.
LOCATION:Patrick G. and Shirley W. Ryan Center for the Musical Arts\, 70 A
 rts Circle\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://www.music.northwestern.edu/events/raphaella-smits-guitar-0
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Three Steps Forward\, Two Steps Back: The Continued Struggle to Tr
 eat Mental Illness in America
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T050000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T050000Z
UID:3350bf2ce0a422ba218cabc6a69ecc81@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:On display in the Eckenhoff Reading Room: Like a path through 
 a maze\, medical and societal responses to mental illness in America have 
 seen shifts and turns of imperfect progress. This exhibit explores both so
 cietal and medical treatments of mental illness in the US from the 18th ce
 ntury to today. It highlights institutional confinement\, medical and phar
 maceutical treatments\, the development of child psychiatry\, and the shif
 t to police as mental illness first responders. Patterns of advancement an
 d retreat carry through each case\, showing the struggle to properly treat
  mental illness continues today. \n\nThis exhibit was created to compleme
 nt the National Library of Medicine’s traveling exhibit\, Care & Custody
 : Past Responses to Mental Health\, on display in the Galter Library atriu
 m February 9-March 21\, 2026. Details about that exhibit are available her
 e.
LOCATION:Ward Building\, 303 E. Chicago Avenue\, Chicago\, IL
URL:https://galter.northwestern.edu/exhibits/28
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Hamdia Traoré’s “Des marabouts de Djenné” and Muslim Portr
 aiture in Mali
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T170000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T220000Z
UID:11f22a545dcc6e01ec810d8721de6f93@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:The storied city of Djenné\, a center of Islamic learning\, s
 tudy\, and scholarship since the twelfth century\, is the hometown of Bama
 ko-based photographer Hamdia Traoré (b. 1992\, Mali). The thirty portrait
 s in Traore’s series Des marabouts de Djenné (Marabouts of Jenne) refle
 ct his intimate connections to the city’s people and deep history. Learn
 ed and devout\, marabouts teach in Djenné’s over 50 Qur’anic schools\
 , offer spiritual guidance\, and treat ailments through their knowledge of
  the Qur’an.\nMade during a time of political and social upheaval in Mal
 i\, these portraits reflect enduring cultural resilience. Each image depic
 ts a marabout seated with the tools of his practice—books\, Qur’an boa
 rds\, amulets\, and prayer beads—framed by the architecture and atmosphe
 re of Djenné. The consistent format underscores their collective identity
 \, while individual poses and captions highlight personal roles and neighb
 orhoods.\nTraoré’s work will be shown alongside mid-20th-century black-
 and-white portraits of marabouts by Malian photographers Mamadou Cissé\, 
 Abdourahmane Sakaly\, and Tijani Sitou. Drawn from the Archive of Malian P
 hotography\, these earlier images share visual parallels and deepen the hi
 storical context. Together\, these images illuminate evolving perspectives
  on spiritual authority\, identity\, and visual representation in Mali.\n\
 nHamdia Traoré’s “Des marabouts de Djenné” and Muslim Portraiture 
 in Mali” is curated by Kathleen Bickford Berzock\, Associate Director of
  Curatorial Affairs\, The Block Museum of Art\, Northwestern University\, 
 in collaboration with Candace M. Keller\, Associate Professor\, Art Histor
 y & Visual Culture\, Michigan State University.  We are grateful to the A
 rchive of Malian Photography (https://amp.matrix.msu.edu/)\, which provide
 d digital scans of archival works. At The Block\, the exhibition is suppor
 ted by the Kadin/Spiegel Family Endowed Fund and a grant from the Illinois
  Arts Council.
LOCATION:Block Museum of Art\, Mary and Leigh\, 40 Arts Circle Drive\, Eva
 nston\, IL
URL:https://www.blockmuseum.northwestern.edu/exhibitions/2026/hamdia-traor
 %C3%A9.html
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
