BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:ISITA | The Chronicles of Two West African Kingdoms - Zachary Wrig
 ht\, Ali Diakite\, Mauro Nobili
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260423T170000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260423T181500Z
UID:542ed74309c77c6d373cd3dc3c1596e8@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Join the Institute for the Study of Islamic Thought in Africa 
 (ISITA) for a talk in our Islam in Africa - New Books in the Field series.
  \nLunch will be served at the talk.\nMauro Nobili\, Zachary Wright\, and
  Ali Diakite will discuss their new book\, The Chronicles of Two West Afri
 can Kingdoms: TheTārīkh Ibn Al-Mukhtār of the Songhay Empire and the T
 ārīkh Al-Fattāsh of the Caliphate of Ḥamdallāhi (The British Academy
  / Liverpool University Press\, 2025).\nDescription: The Chronicles of Tw
 o West African Kingdoms presents a new reading of West African history fro
 m the fifteenth to the nineteenth centuries. Based on close analysis of Ar
 abic manuscripts from Timbuktu and other regions\, this volume provides ke
 y historical context from the Songhay Empire through the Caliphate of Ḥa
 mdallāhi\, along with translations and Arabic editions of the long-obscur
 ed Tārīkh Ibn al-Mukhtār in parallel with the later production known as
  the Tārīkh al-fattāsh. The central observation that emerges from these
  texts is that Muslim scholars in premodern West Africa\, who saw themselv
 es as constitutive to the powerful kingdoms in the Western Sudan\, claimed
  almost unprecedented authority to shape reality through narration.\nDr. M
 auro Nobili is Professor of History at the University of Illinois at Urban
 a-Champaign.\nDr. Ali Diakite is Cataloger for West African Manuscripts at
  the Hill Museum and Manuscript Library (Collegeville\, MN).\nDr. Zachary 
 Wright is ISITA's Director\, as well as Professor in Residence and Associa
 te Dean for Faculty Affairs at Northwestern University in Qatar.
LOCATION:Harris Hall\, 1881 Sheridan Road\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://planitpurple.northwestern.edu/event/638332
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Teresa Montoya’s Tó Łitso (Yellow Water): Ten Years after the 
